= Sounds and spelling

Dutch uses the same alphabet as English, but some letter combinations sound very different. At the beginning, it is enough to recognize the most common spelling patterns.

== Long and short vowels

#let vowel-table = table(
  columns: 3,
  table.header[Spelling][Rough value][Example],
  [a], [short "a"], [man],
  [aa], [long "a"], [maan],
  [e], [short "e"], [bed],
  [ee], [long "e"], [been],
  [o], [short "o"], [bos],
  [oo], [long "o"], [boom],
  [u], [short rounded vowel], [bus],
  [uu], [long rounded vowel], [muur],
)

#figure(caption: [Common vowel patterns], vowel-table)

In one-syllable words, long vowels are often written double: `maan`, `been`, `boom`. In longer words, a single vowel can still be long when the syllable is open: `lo-pen`, `ta-fel`, `mu-ren`.

== Useful sound combinations

- `oe` sounds like English *oo* in *moon*: `boek`, `goed`
- `eu` is rounded and has no exact English match: `leuk`, `neus`
- `ui` is one of the hardest Dutch sounds for beginners: `huis`, `tuin`
- `ij` and `ei` usually sound alike in modern speech: `mijn`, `reis`
- `g` and `ch` are often pronounced with a throat sound: `goed`, `nacht`
- `sch` appears often at the start of words: `school`, `schip`

== Stress

Many native Dutch words are stressed on the first syllable: `tafel`, `lopen`, `werken`. Loanwords can behave differently, so do not force every word into the same rhythm.

For now, the main goal is recognition. If you can connect spelling to sound reasonably well, reading becomes much easier.
